it's something we've been talking about
for a while, and--and--

243
00:11:37,906 --> 00:11:40,408
'Cause I don't know if we want the girls
to grow up in this city.

244
00:11:40,450 --> 00:11:42,994
- I mean, is that--
- Well, the suburbs I could understand.

245
00:11:43,078 --> 00:11:46,206
Yeah, but I just like
the idea of the country.

246
00:11:46,289 --> 00:11:47,791
You know? It appeals to me.

247
00:11:47,874 --> 00:11:50,168
You know, it's--it's safe, it's quiet.

248
00:11:50,251 --> 00:11:51,753
I could do my writing there.

249
00:11:51,836 --> 00:11:55,465
What does that mean, a farm?
You'd have like, what, chickens?

250
00:11:55,507 --> 00:11:57,050
No, no, no. Not chickens.

251
00:11:57,133 --> 00:11:58,343
It's not a farm. It's just--

252
00:11:58,426 --> 00:11:59,803
Yeah, I mean,
you could grow stuff if you want.

253
00:11:59,844 --> 00:12:02,055
You could grow tomatoes or corn
or something, I'm sure.

254
00:12:02,138 --> 00:12:03,556
In upstate New York?

255
00:12:03,640 --> 00:12:05,100
Yeah, you could--Why not?

256
00:12:05,183 --> 00:12:07,894
Well, New Jersey has the fantastic corn.

257
00:12:07,977 --> 00:12:10,146
All right, well, you know what?
The point isn't to grow corn--

258
00:12:10,230 --> 00:12:12,148
New York is, I think,
maybe too cold for corn.

259
00:12:12,190 --> 00:12:15,276
Forget I said corn. Drop the corn.
The point is the house.

260
00:12:15,318 --> 00:12:16,903
You go, and it's a house
in the country, so--

261
00:12:16,986 --> 00:12:19,322
- It sounds like a nice thing.
- Yeah, I understand.

262
00:12:19,406 --> 00:12:20,740
Just a quiet place in the country.

263
00:12:20,824 --> 00:12:23,284
Yeah, yeah. That's all.
A house in the country.

264
00:12:23,326 --> 00:12:27,539
Well, you're not gonna buy it
without looking at it first, though, right?

265
00:12:27,622 --> 00:12:31,126
What are we doing? We're going--
We're driving to go look at it, right?

266
00:12:31,209 --> 00:12:33,670
'Cause, you know, you never know.

267
00:12:33,753 --> 00:12:36,798
No, I know. I know.

268
00:12:40,135 --> 00:12:41,553
So, what do you know?

269
00:12:41,636 --> 00:12:43,972
I had a thought,
but no one wanted to hear it.

270
00:12:44,014 --> 00:12:45,140
What?

271
00:12:45,181 --> 00:12:47,058
Well, if she's that fed up
with your father...

272
00:12:47,142 --> 00:12:51,563
wouldn't she maybe want to look up
an old boyfriend or something?

273
00:12:51,646 --> 00:12:53,273
No.
That's my mother we're talking about.

274
00:12:53,356 --> 00:12:55,191
I'm not saying
she had a lover or anything.

275
00:12:55,233 --> 00:12:58,987
Please. Please. Whoever she's gonna
call is already married or dead.

276
00:12:59,029 --> 00:13:00,989
I should just turn around and
come home right now, shouldn't I?

277
00:13:01,031 --> 00:13:03,074
No, no. Let us look for her.

278
00:13:03,158 --> 00:13:05,744
You're doing the best thing
for your dad right now.

279
00:13:05,827 --> 00:13:08,288
- How's he doing?
- He's, you know...

280
00:13:08,371 --> 00:13:11,374
I hit the sink thing!
It sprayed all over me!

281
00:13:11,458 --> 00:13:12,751
What? What's happening?

282
00:13:12,834 --> 00:13:14,044
- Uh...oy.
- How is he?

283
00:13:14,127 --> 00:13:16,171
Damn sink sprayed me, but good.

284
00:13:16,254 --> 00:13:17,380
Hon?

285
00:13:17,464 --> 00:13:19,758
I don't know. He--

286
00:13:19,841 --> 00:13:22,052
- He looks older.
- He is.

287
00:13:22,135 --> 00:13:23,428
Who's that? Rachel?

288
00:13:23,511 --> 00:13:24,721
- Yeah.
- Anything?

289
00:13:24,804 --> 00:13:25,972
Nothing yet.

290
00:13:26,056 --> 00:13:29,726
Hey, you know what?
Try and have fun with him today.

291
00:13:29,768 --> 00:13:33,229
You always say
you never had time together, right?

292
00:13:33,313 --> 00:13:35,857
So, maybe this is...the good thing.

293
00:13:35,899 --> 00:13:38,151
All right. Here he comes. Gotta go.

294
00:13:38,234 --> 00:13:39,778
OK, take it easy. I love you.

295
00:13:39,861 --> 00:13:41,363
- Love you, too.
- All right.

296
00:13:47,577 --> 00:13:50,455
So, it's OK?
You can take a day off like this?

297
00:13:50,538 --> 00:13:53,249
Yeah, yeah, yeah. I just had
a magazine piece that was due.

298
00:13:53,333 --> 00:13:55,794
I just turned that in yesterday,
so I'm good.

299
00:13:55,877 --> 00:13:58,672
And your book? It's still, uh...

300
00:13:58,755 --> 00:14:00,423
The book? No, no.
No, working on the book.

301
00:14:00,465 --> 00:14:02,133
Still writing, yeah. But it's--

302
00:14:02,217 --> 00:14:03,760
You know, listen,
three and a half years in...

303
00:14:03,843 --> 00:14:06,846
and taking one afternoon off
is not gonna kill me.

304
00:14:06,930 --> 00:14:09,349
You know, I went into the bookstore
in the mall.

305
00:14:09,432 --> 00:14:10,558
- Oh, yeah, yeah?
- Yeah.

306
00:14:10,600 --> 00:14:12,686
I thought I'd see
if they had your other book.

307
00:14:12,769 --> 00:14:15,146
- Ha ha. OK. And?
- They don't.

308
00:14:15,230 --> 00:14:17,649
They don't. Oh, well.
No, they don't carry everything.

309
00:14:17,732 --> 00:14:20,110
The big stores--You know,
in the mall, they're not gonna--

310
00:14:20,193 --> 00:14:22,821
You know who they have a lot of?
John Grisham.

311
00:14:22,904 --> 00:14:26,032
My God. This guy--
one book after another, this guy!

312
00:14:26,116 --> 00:14:28,451
He's fast. He's fast.

313
00:14:34,290 --> 00:14:37,002
How'd you know it was me?

314
00:14:41,965 --> 00:14:43,883
I think this is it.

315
00:14:43,967 --> 00:14:46,511
- Wow.
- Plenty of room here.

316
00:14:46,594 --> 00:14:49,097
Look at this!

317
00:14:49,139 --> 00:14:51,182
Do you believe
this is all the same place?

318
00:14:51,266 --> 00:14:53,768
Lot of mowing and pruning.

319
00:14:53,810 --> 00:14:57,188
You're gonna have to get
one of those mowers with a chair on it.

320
00:14:57,272 --> 00:14:59,858
Ha ha ha! Oh, wow.

321
00:14:59,941 --> 00:15:01,651
So, this would be the driveway.

322
00:15:01,735 --> 00:15:05,071
You hear that? Listen to that.
The pebbles against the tires.

323
00:15:05,155 --> 00:15:06,906
- Gravel is good.
- Oh, yeah.

324
00:15:08,908 --> 00:15:11,953
Oh, I like this. I like this.

325
00:15:13,913 --> 00:15:15,498
Mr. Harrison?

326
00:15:15,582 --> 00:15:18,168
That I am. Mr. Kleinman?

327
00:15:18,251 --> 00:15:19,878
- Yes, sir!
- That's me.

328
00:15:19,961 --> 00:15:21,838
Hi. Ben Kleinman.

329
00:15:21,880 --> 00:15:22,922
Well, hello.

330
00:15:23,006 --> 00:15:24,341
Hi. This is my father.

331
00:15:24,382 --> 00:15:26,593
- Sam Kleinman. How are you?
- Pleasure.

332
00:15:26,676 --> 00:15:28,345
You've got a spectacular place here.

333
00:15:28,428 --> 00:15:30,347
- Thank you.
- Yes, sir.

334
00:15:32,098 --> 00:15:34,934
Uh...oh, uh, I'll tell you...

335
00:15:35,018 --> 00:15:38,271
why don't you two fellas talk,
and I'll just mosey around?

336
00:15:38,355 --> 00:15:40,190
Terrific. Great. Thank you.

337
00:15:40,231 --> 00:15:41,941
Well, shall I show you around?

338
00:15:42,025 --> 00:15:44,361
Please. That would be just terrific.

339
00:15:44,402 --> 00:15:46,363
How was your trip up? All right?

340
00:15:46,446 --> 00:15:48,865
My great-grandmother's family...

341
00:15:48,907 --> 00:15:50,992
gave her this land
on her eighteenth birthday.

342
00:15:51,076 --> 00:15:52,285
Is that right? Huh.

343
00:15:52,369 --> 00:15:55,288
And my great-grandfather
built the house with his own hands.

344
00:15:55,372 --> 00:15:57,624
- Really?
- Right after the Civil War.

345
00:15:57,707 --> 00:16:01,252
Wow. It's just--
It's a magical place.

346
00:16:01,336 --> 00:16:03,129
It's important that you feel that way.

347
00:16:03,213 --> 00:16:05,965
Oh, I do. I do. Heh.

348
00:16:19,979 --> 00:16:22,816
My father and I
shot moose and wild boar...

349
00:16:22,899 --> 00:16:24,734
just inside those woods over there.

350
00:16:24,818 --> 00:16:26,194
Wow. Heh.

351
00:16:26,236 --> 00:16:29,155
The moose are gone now, by and large.

352
00:16:29,239 --> 00:16:31,991
Time marches on,
with or without our consent.

353
00:16:32,075 --> 00:16:33,076
Hmm.

354
00:16:33,159 --> 00:16:35,286
I will tell you this, though--

355
00:16:35,370 --> 00:16:37,872
whoever lives here next...

356
00:16:37,914 --> 00:16:42,043
will have the finest golden corner
of God's green earth.

357
00:16:42,085 --> 00:16:44,587
Boy, you got some place here!

358
00:16:44,629 --> 00:16:46,047
That lake? Ooh!

359
00:16:46,089 --> 00:16:47,382
We've been very blessed.

360
00:16:47,424 --> 00:16:50,051
Let me ask you something.
The septic tank--

361
00:16:50,093 --> 00:16:51,928
what kind of system
did they put in here?

362
00:16:52,012 --> 00:16:53,054
Do you know?

363
00:16:53,096 --> 00:16:54,806
I beg your pardon?

364
00:16:54,889 --> 00:16:57,392
I mean, it doesn't drain
right into the lake, does it?

365
00:16:57,434 --> 00:17:00,186
Because I see the other houses
up on the hill there...

366
00:17:00,270 --> 00:17:05,400
and I got to figure, if all that's draining
into your water--oh, boy.

367
00:17:05,442 --> 00:17:11,614
Come the hot weather,
this place is gonna stink to high hell.

368
00:17:19,706 --> 00:17:21,332
Let me tell you something.

369
00:17:21,416 --> 00:17:25,628
If a guy is selling you a house,
and he don't want you to ask questions...

370
00:17:25,670 --> 00:17:27,422
you don't want the house.

371
00:17:27,464 --> 00:17:29,007
- Right.
- Am I wrong?

372
00:17:29,090 --> 00:17:30,425
No. I'm saying--you're right.

373
00:17:30,467 --> 00:17:32,844
Your old man is not as dumb
as you think, you know.

374
00:17:32,927 --> 00:17:34,846
Your mother and I,
we looked at a house once.

375
00:17:34,929 --> 00:17:36,264
I know. Lakewood.

376
00:17:36,306 --> 00:17:38,183
Lakewood, New Jersey. That's right.

377
00:17:38,266 --> 00:17:40,894
We got the money into escrow,
we run an inspection...

378
00:17:40,977 --> 00:17:42,312
what do we find?

379
00:17:42,354 --> 00:17:43,438
Rats.

380
00:17:43,480 --> 00:17:46,107
You'd better believe it.
Floor to ceiling.

381
00:17:46,149 --> 00:17:47,734
The place was infested.

382
00:17:47,817 --> 00:17:51,154
So believe me,
there is always a reason.

383
00:17:51,237 --> 00:17:54,199
- Always.
- You're darn tootin'.

384
00:17:54,282 --> 00:17:56,743
- There's always a reason.
- Right.

385
00:17:56,826 --> 00:17:59,496
- And there's never not a reason.
- What?

386
00:17:59,579 --> 00:18:03,333
Right? So, what you're saying is,
there really--there is no house...

387
00:18:03,375 --> 00:18:06,044
that anyone could buy anywhere, ever.

388
00:18:06,127 --> 00:18:07,212
- What?
- Right?

389
00:18:07,295 --> 00:18:10,173
I mean, all over the world.
All over the world, no matter where...

390
00:18:10,215 --> 00:18:12,092
no matter when,
there just is no house...

391
00:18:12,175 --> 00:18:13,635
that anybody should buy,
you're saying...

392
00:18:13,677 --> 00:18:15,261
because it--it's always a trick.

393
00:18:15,345 --> 00:18:16,846
There's always some kind of scam.

394
00:18:16,930 --> 00:18:19,683
- What are you talking about?
- So, therefore--therefore, what?

395
00:18:19,766 --> 00:18:21,059
Don't even try?

396
00:18:21,142 --> 00:18:23,019
Try what? I don't know
what you're saying now.

397
00:18:23,103 --> 00:18:25,522
That's your big plan,
is don't have a dream...

398
00:18:25,605 --> 00:18:28,191
'cause if you have a dream,
it'll only turn to shit.

399
00:18:28,274 --> 00:18:29,818
Yeah, just leave things how they are.

400
00:18:29,859 --> 00:18:32,821
We'll leave things how they are--nice--
and then wait till it's too late.

401
00:18:32,862 --> 00:18:34,072
Till what's too late?

402
00:18:34,155 --> 00:18:36,032
Yeah, just wait
till everybody's dead, right?

403
00:18:36,116 --> 00:18:38,368
What are you gettin' so upset about?

404
00:18:38,410 --> 00:18:40,704
- OK, that's why Mom left.
- Why?

405
00:18:40,787 --> 00:18:42,205
You want to know why? Because of this.

406
00:18:42,288 --> 00:18:45,417
- Because of what?
- Because of this. Because of you.

407
00:18:45,500 --> 00:18:47,877
You got a reason not to do everything.

408
00:18:47,961 --> 00:18:50,755
Whatever it is, there's a reason--
''No, you can't do that.''

409
00:18:50,839 --> 00:18:52,382
She wanted a house in the country...

410
00:18:52,465 --> 00:18:55,343
but you said, ''No, the kids are too little.''
Right? And then, all of a sudden...

411
00:18:55,385 --> 00:18:58,221
''No, the kids are grown up.
We don't need a house in the country.''

412
00:18:58,263 --> 00:19:01,099
She wanted to travel, but no--
''This place is too far.

413
00:19:01,182 --> 00:19:03,059
That place, it's not far enough.''

414
00:19:03,101 --> 00:19:07,063
Right? ''The winter-- it's too cold.
The summer--it's so crowded there.

415
00:19:07,105 --> 00:19:08,273
The spring--it's rainy.''

416
00:19:08,356 --> 00:19:11,484
Whatever it is. But you know what?
Somebody goes to these places!

417
00:19:11,568 --> 00:19:13,403
Somebody's buying
these houses in the country!

418
00:19:13,445 --> 00:19:17,032
So I gotta think
it can't be that fucking horrible!

419
00:19:17,073 --> 00:19:18,825
You know, you're talkin' out of your ass--

420
00:19:18,908 --> 00:19:20,785
Oh, am I? Yeah, OK.

421
00:19:20,869 --> 00:19:23,163
When you're married forty years,
come talk to me.

422
00:19:23,246 --> 00:19:26,416
Please. It's not the forty years.
It was always like this. You know that.

423
00:19:26,499 --> 00:19:27,625
- Oh, really?
- Yes, yes.

424
00:19:27,709 --> 00:19:29,753
It was like this before I was born.

425
00:19:29,836 --> 00:19:33,214
How do you know what the hell
things were like before you were born?

426
00:19:33,256 --> 00:19:35,759
I--I--Just trust me, I know. I know.

427
00:19:35,800 --> 00:19:37,218
- You know?
- Yes, I know.

428
00:19:37,260 --> 00:19:40,055
Well, I'm telling you you don't know
what you're talking about.

429
00:19:40,096 --> 00:19:41,514
Oh, OK.
I don't know what I'm talking about?

430
00:19:41,598 --> 00:19:42,599
- Do me a favor.
- Really?

431
00:19:42,682 --> 00:19:45,310
Why don't you close your mouth
and drive me back to the city?

432
00:19:45,393 --> 00:19:46,394
I don't know what I'm talking about?

433
00:19:46,436 --> 00:19:47,896
Good. Now, let me
show you something.

434
00:19:47,937 --> 00:19:50,565
Let's take a look.
Let's see how much I don't know.

435
00:19:50,648 --> 00:19:52,567
Keep your eye on the road!
Watch where you're driving!

436
00:19:52,609 --> 00:19:53,693
I want you to see something.

437
00:19:53,777 --> 00:19:56,446
- Hey. Hey! Jesus!
- Shit!

438
00:20:04,579 --> 00:20:07,290
Whew. You all right?

439
00:20:07,374 --> 00:20:08,416
Yeah.

440
00:20:08,500 --> 00:20:11,294
Yeah. You OK?

441
00:20:11,378 --> 00:20:13,129
I'm fine.

442
00:20:30,897 --> 00:20:32,315
Jesus.

443
00:20:33,483 --> 00:20:34,651
Oh, boy.

444
00:20:38,279 --> 00:20:39,447
That's good.

445
00:20:39,489 --> 00:20:41,241
Hey.

446
00:20:41,324 --> 00:20:44,202
A new car you can always get.

447
00:20:46,204 --> 00:20:47,664
I'm sorry.

448
00:20:50,667 --> 00:20:54,004
So, what were you gonna show me?

449
00:20:54,045 --> 00:20:55,338
Nothing.

450
00:20:55,422 --> 00:20:59,551
Now you got my attention. Heh.

451
00:21:05,306 --> 00:21:06,850
OK.

452
00:21:25,035 --> 00:21:26,119
What's this?

453
00:21:26,202 --> 00:21:27,662
It's for you.

454
00:21:27,704 --> 00:21:28,955
From you?

455
00:21:29,039 --> 00:21:30,749
It's from Mom.

456
00:21:30,832 --> 00:21:33,084
What, she's leaving me again now?

457
00:21:33,168 --> 00:21:35,170
It was so much fun the first time?

458
00:21:37,047 --> 00:21:41,509
She wrote this--She wrote this
the year I was born.

459
00:21:41,551 --> 00:21:44,554
She wrote it,
but she never gave it to you.

460
00:21:44,637 --> 00:21:46,014
So, how did you get it?

461
00:21:46,056 --> 00:21:48,725
When I was fourteen, I was digging
around in her nightstand drawer.

462
00:21:48,808 --> 00:21:49,976
I was gonna steal a cigarette.

463
00:21:50,060 --> 00:21:51,436
Your mother doesn't smoke.

464
00:21:51,519 --> 00:21:54,397
Not smoke smoke,
but she used to--once in a while.

465
00:21:54,481 --> 00:21:57,776
She had the same pack of Newport Lights
in there for seven years.

466
00:21:57,859 --> 00:22:00,862
I never knew your mother smoked.

467
00:22:00,904 --> 00:22:02,655
Well, there you go.

468
00:22:02,739 --> 00:22:04,199
So, you took this?

469
00:22:04,240 --> 00:22:07,869
Yeah. I still don't know
if she ever noticed it was gone.

470
00:22:07,911 --> 00:22:10,163
And you keep this in the car?

471
00:22:11,456 --> 00:22:13,625
No. I don't keep it in the c--

472
00:22:13,708 --> 00:22:16,878
I dug it up to show it to you,
because I thought--

473
00:22:16,920 --> 00:22:20,507
'Cause I--I don't know why.
Because I figured it was time.

474
00:22:23,343 --> 00:22:25,095
''March 18--''

475
00:22:26,346 --> 00:22:30,600
But that's two weeks
before you were born.

476
00:22:35,355 --> 00:22:36,940
Why...

477
00:22:38,066 --> 00:22:39,818
Just read.

478
00:22:46,282 --> 00:22:47,867
Sam...

479
00:22:47,951 --> 00:22:50,662
this is the letter that should
be pinned to a pillow...

480
00:22:50,745 --> 00:22:56,167
explaining why the wife has run off
and left her husband.

481
00:22:56,251 --> 00:22:58,753
But I have nobody to run off with...

482
00:22:58,795 --> 00:23:00,088
nor can I run off.

483
00:23:00,130 --> 00:23:05,093
Apparently, my life isn't even
my own to do away with.

484
00:23:06,594 --> 00:23:10,098
In my heart,
I must take leave of you now...

485
00:23:10,140 --> 00:23:14,477
because unless I disentangle myself
from you emotionally...

486
00:23:14,561 --> 00:23:17,522
I'll never be a fit mother for our children.

487
00:23:18,940 --> 00:23:22,777
I don't think you could measure
all the tears I've shed.

488
00:23:22,819 --> 00:23:24,446
When I've needed you most...

489
00:23:24,529 --> 00:23:29,117
you have found it more pressing
to be anywhere else but with me.

490
00:23:30,410 --> 00:23:32,454
But I know it wasn't always so.

491
00:23:32,537 --> 00:23:35,623
I know the world
was once vibrant with promise.

492
00:23:35,665 --> 00:23:40,337
After all, wasn't I the girl,
fresh out of college...

493
00:23:40,420 --> 00:23:43,006
who got the job at the very first
interview she ever had?

494
00:23:45,342 --> 00:23:49,846
So what if I cancelled my plans
to go see the World's Fair in Queens?

495
00:23:49,929 --> 00:23:52,515
I was working in Manhattan...

496
00:23:52,599 --> 00:23:55,727
and making $1 3 a week to boot.

497
00:23:55,810 --> 00:23:59,981
And how thrilling that you,
a handsome young boss...

498
00:24:00,023 --> 00:24:02,025
were interested in me.

499
00:24:05,862 --> 00:24:07,238
When you went in the army...

500
00:24:07,322 --> 00:24:10,533
I did everything I could
to keep that office running...

501
00:24:10,575 --> 00:24:13,203
because I was sure
this was the way to your heart.

502
00:24:14,621 --> 00:24:17,957
How all the more humiliating
it was for me, then...

503
00:24:18,041 --> 00:24:20,335
to watch you spend
your weekend furloughs...

504
00:24:20,377 --> 00:24:22,629
catching up on business...

505
00:24:22,712 --> 00:24:25,465
while I got the final fifteen minutes
at Penn Station...

506
00:24:25,548 --> 00:24:27,384
before you shipped out again.

507
00:24:29,719 --> 00:24:33,348
I must have loved you an awful lot
to have been so hurt.

508
00:24:34,557 --> 00:24:37,102
In fact, sometimes I almost wish...

509
00:24:37,185 --> 00:24:39,104
you would have yourself
a love affair...

510
00:24:39,187 --> 00:24:42,148
so that you would know
how the heart can be affected.

511
00:24:43,400 --> 00:24:47,112
Oh, I guess you loved me
in your way...

512
00:24:47,195 --> 00:24:49,489
as part of the whole picture--

513
00:24:49,572 --> 00:24:52,909
a comfortable life taken for granted.

514
00:24:55,870 --> 00:24:59,582
But believe me, it's not enough.

515
00:24:59,666 --> 00:25:02,877
Maybe it's all I'm meant to get...

516
00:25:02,919 --> 00:25:08,717
but, please, don't let anybody
ever treat our girls this way.

517
00:25:11,177 --> 00:25:14,639
From here on,
I'll stop hoping you'll change.

518
00:25:16,433 --> 00:25:19,769
I won't expect evenings
to be different from each other...

519
00:25:19,811 --> 00:25:22,439
nor weekends different from workdays.

520
00:25:22,522 --> 00:25:24,566
I won't expect anything anymore.

521
00:25:24,607 --> 00:25:28,570
But you have destroyed a marriage.

522
00:25:32,282 --> 00:25:38,246
P.S.: Congratulations.
You finally have your son.

523
00:25:38,288 --> 00:25:40,457
I hope he brings you much pleasure.

524
00:25:40,540 --> 00:25:43,460
As for me, I'm glad he's here...

525
00:25:43,543 --> 00:25:45,879
but I still miss your tenderness...

526
00:25:45,962 --> 00:25:49,632
your thoughtfulness,
even your politeness.

527
00:25:49,716 --> 00:25:54,012
I don't know if you have it in you,
but I yearn for it.

528
00:25:54,095 --> 00:25:59,225
Maybe someday, when
you have nothing else on your mind.

529
00:26:21,414 --> 00:26:22,999
Bullshit.

530
00:26:24,167 --> 00:26:25,502
What?

531
00:26:25,543 --> 00:26:27,420
Bullshit.

532
00:26:28,588 --> 00:26:30,048
What do you mean, bullshit?

533
00:26:30,131 --> 00:26:35,387
I'm saying that this is a crock of b-u-l-l--
bullshit!

534
00:26:35,470 --> 00:26:38,473
That is not the way it was.

535
00:26:38,515 --> 00:26:40,975
- How what was?
- All of it!

536
00:26:42,102 --> 00:26:44,229
- Well--
- Bullshit!

537
00:26:44,312 --> 00:26:45,897
You think it was like that?

538
00:26:45,980 --> 00:26:49,275
I don't know what it was like,
but that's--that's what she wrote.

539
00:26:49,359 --> 00:26:51,277
I mean, that's--that's what she felt.

540
00:26:51,361 --> 00:26:53,488
That I'm a prick?

541
00:26:53,530 --> 00:26:56,408
Your father is such a callous...

542
00:26:56,491 --> 00:26:59,369
uncaring son of a bitch...

543
00:26:59,411 --> 00:27:01,371
that he ruined the marriage...

544
00:27:01,454 --> 00:27:04,374
that he made your mother
that miserable?

545
00:27:05,709 --> 00:27:08,670
Let me tell you something,
sonny boy.

546
00:27:08,712 --> 00:27:12,924
I busted my ass
building that business.

547
00:27:13,008 --> 00:27:14,300
You're damn right.

548
00:27:14,384 --> 00:27:18,430
You know what Crown Carpet was
when we started?

549
00:27:18,513 --> 00:27:20,724
Two guys, a desk, and a clipboard.

550
00:27:20,807 --> 00:27:21,891
That was it!

551
00:27:21,975 --> 00:27:24,352
Did I have to stay at the office
late a lot?

552
00:27:24,394 --> 00:27:26,062
You bet I did.

553
00:27:26,146 --> 00:27:28,523
Did I have to travel
all over the goddamn place...

554
00:27:28,565 --> 00:27:30,275
here and there,
drummin' up business?

555
00:27:30,358 --> 00:27:31,693
You bet I did.

556
00:27:31,735 --> 00:27:34,237
Because that's what had to be done!

557
00:27:36,072 --> 00:27:38,074
So, did I miss out on a lot of nice things?

558
00:27:38,158 --> 00:27:41,703
Yes, I missed out on a lot of nice things.

559
00:27:41,745 --> 00:27:44,873
Does that make me uncaring?

560
00:27:44,956 --> 00:27:47,125
A rotten husband?

561
00:27:47,208 --> 00:27:49,461
A rotten father?

562
00:27:51,838 --> 00:27:54,090
Crown Carpets fed you kids...

563
00:27:54,174 --> 00:27:57,761
sent you to the best schools,
the best summer camps.

564
00:27:57,844 --> 00:28:01,348
Who of your friends ever went away
to such nice places, huh?

565
00:28:01,431 --> 00:28:05,018
Mexico, Puerto Rico that time...

566
00:28:05,101 --> 00:28:07,896
Hershey, Pennsylvania.

567
00:28:07,937 --> 00:28:10,774
Who was that for? For me?

568
00:28:10,815 --> 00:28:15,028
I need to take a vacation
to see another factory?

569
00:28:15,111 --> 00:28:17,238
To see how they make chocolate?

570
00:28:17,322 --> 00:28:23,286
I don't give a shit how they make it,
but I went for you and for the family.

571
00:28:23,370 --> 00:28:27,874
Don't you dare tell me
I wasn't there for you kids.

572
00:28:29,250 --> 00:28:31,544
She never got to go to the World's Fair.

573
00:28:31,628 --> 00:28:33,463
That's my fault.

574
00:28:33,546 --> 00:28:34,798
Fifty years later.

575
00:28:34,839 --> 00:28:38,301
You want to go to the World's Fair?
Go! Who's stopping you?

576
00:28:38,385 --> 00:28:40,929
That I had an affair. Bullshit!

577
00:28:40,970 --> 00:28:43,890
- No, she didn't say that you had an--
- Never!

578
00:28:43,973 --> 00:28:45,141
- She said that--
- Never!

579
00:28:45,225 --> 00:28:47,227
What she said was
she almost wishes you had.

580
00:28:47,310 --> 00:28:50,105
She wishes I had.
What kind of craziness is that?

581
00:28:50,146 --> 00:28:53,149
She wishes you had, so then
you would've known what--what it--

582
00:28:53,233 --> 00:28:56,236
That is pure crazy shit.

583
00:28:56,319 --> 00:29:00,407
Never so much as a dalliance.

584
00:29:00,490 --> 00:29:02,826
Never.

585
00:29:05,995 --> 00:29:08,623
The other fellas, yes.

586
00:29:08,707 --> 00:29:11,793
I'm not saying
it's unheard of in the office.

587
00:29:11,876 --> 00:29:13,545
I'm not an innocent.
Bernie Kaye--

588
00:29:13,628 --> 00:29:15,880
you remember Bernie Kaye,
the sales rep?

589
00:29:15,964 --> 00:29:20,093
Shtupped everything that moved
between Baltimore and Syracuse.

590
00:29:20,176 --> 00:29:22,137
Legendary cocksman.

591
00:29:22,220 --> 00:29:23,638
Boasted about it.

592
00:29:23,680 --> 00:29:27,892
And his wife, by the way, adores him.

593
00:29:27,976 --> 00:29:30,603
Thinks he's the greatest thing
since Ovaltine.

594
00:29:30,687 --> 00:29:36,985
But me--me, who never once so much
as laid a finger on another woman...

595
00:29:37,027 --> 00:29:41,614
me, your mother had to run away
from after 47 years...

596
00:29:41,698 --> 00:29:46,119
because I'm such
an unconscionable prick.

597
00:29:50,957 --> 00:29:52,584
Well, maybe
I shouldn't have shown you--

598
00:29:52,667 --> 00:29:56,087
You're damn right
you shouldn't have shown me!

599
00:29:56,171 --> 00:29:59,049
And look at your car!
You gonna call somebody to fix it?

600
00:29:59,132 --> 00:30:02,177
- I'm gonna call--
- Or is it gonna fix by itself sitting there?

601
00:30:02,218 --> 00:30:06,139
- I'm gonna call someone.
- Good, because I'm goddamn hungry now.

602
00:30:06,222 --> 00:30:09,851
And aggravated. And I have to pee.

603
00:30:09,893 --> 00:30:11,811
And you know what?

604
00:30:11,895 --> 00:30:14,272
I'm gonna pee right here.

605
00:30:14,356 --> 00:30:15,774
Go ahead.

606
00:30:15,857 --> 00:30:17,650
You're damn right I'm goin' ahead!

607
00:30:17,734 --> 00:30:22,113
And I don't need permission from you.

608
00:30:23,239 --> 00:30:25,492
You hear that, everybody?!

609
00:30:25,575 --> 00:30:28,745
Sam Kleinman, Fair Lawn, New Jersey...

610
00:30:28,828 --> 00:30:32,499
and I'm gonna pee
wherever I goddamn please!

611
00:30:43,093 --> 00:30:47,305
That really burns my ass.

612
00:30:47,389 --> 00:30:49,766
I'm not polite?

613
00:30:49,849 --> 00:30:52,310
Who's more polite than me?

614
00:30:53,645 --> 00:30:55,480
Come on, tell me.

615
00:30:57,107 --> 00:31:00,944
That really burns my ass.

616
00:31:10,620 --> 00:31:12,455
You're lucky I heard the phone
when I did.

617
00:31:12,497 --> 00:31:14,207
I was nearly halfway to my car.

618
00:31:14,290 --> 00:31:16,167
We're closed for the night.

619
00:31:16,251 --> 00:31:20,171
What do you mean, closed? But you're--
you're gonna fix this first, right?

620
00:31:20,255 --> 00:31:24,259
My wife is making chicken paprikash,
and that is one dish I do not want to miss.

621
00:31:24,300 --> 00:31:26,970
OK. All right, but can you just--
You know what?

622
00:31:27,053 --> 00:31:29,222
If you can just get it
so I can drive it out of here--

623
00:31:29,305 --> 00:31:31,433
Oh, there's no way
we can do anything tonight.

624
00:31:31,474 --> 00:31:34,853
You come back in the morning.
I'll be here at the crack of 7:00.

625
00:31:34,936 --> 00:31:37,439
Oh, no, no. No, no, no, no, no.
I can't stay.

626
00:31:37,480 --> 00:31:39,983
Come on.
You'll stay the night in a nice motel...

627
00:31:40,066 --> 00:31:41,568
and you come back here
in the morning.

628
00:31:41,651 --> 00:31:43,611
What do you say? Come on.

629
00:31:45,321 --> 00:31:47,323
The official said North Korea
has massed--

630
00:31:47,365 --> 00:31:50,744
No, we're fine, we're fine.
Just the car's not so fine.

631
00:31:50,827 --> 00:31:53,663
Jeez, Benny. Don't hit trees with cars.

632
00:31:53,747 --> 00:31:55,874
- I know.
- Trees always win.

633
00:31:55,957 --> 00:31:58,251
Yeah, I know, I know.
How are my girls. They miss me?

634
00:31:58,335 --> 00:31:59,586
You mean since breakfast?

635
00:31:59,669 --> 00:32:01,963
Is that all I'm gone?
Jeez, it feels like a year.

636
00:32:02,005 --> 00:32:07,719
I wonder if Tom Brokaw's wife is upset
because he's working late.

637
00:32:07,802 --> 00:32:09,971
You see his phone ringing off the hook?

638
00:32:10,013 --> 00:32:12,557
''Just wanted you to know
your dinner's cold...

639
00:32:12,640 --> 00:32:14,976
and the children all agree
you're a shitheel.''

640
00:32:15,018 --> 00:32:16,811
- You hearing this?
- Yeah.

641
00:32:16,853 --> 00:32:18,855
Us that work and give and give and give!

642
00:32:18,938 --> 00:32:22,484
- This--This is who I've created.
- A man has to say, ''That's it!

643
00:32:22,567 --> 00:32:24,235
I'm not givin' any more!''

644
00:32:24,319 --> 00:32:25,653
When "Nightly News" continues...

645
00:32:25,695 --> 00:32:28,698
You go, Tom.
You do whatever you have to do.

646
00:32:28,782 --> 00:32:31,951
- I'll wait right here for you.
- Wait, that's the other line. Hang on.

647
00:32:32,035 --> 00:32:34,871
I'm not the kind of person who runs off
because he's bored...

648
00:32:34,954 --> 00:32:37,040
because he needs to find himself.

649
00:32:37,123 --> 00:32:41,378
You know where to find me, my friend--
exactly where I said I'd be.

650
00:32:41,419 --> 00:32:46,091
That's right.
Right here, baby! Right here!

651
00:32:46,174 --> 00:32:47,717
You want a grapefruit juice?

652
00:32:47,801 --> 00:32:49,844
OK, your sisters
are like little detectives now.

653
00:32:49,886 --> 00:32:51,012
Hang on.

654
00:32:51,054 --> 00:32:52,305
- Are you there?
- I'm here.

655
00:32:52,389 --> 00:32:54,641
- Hey, look at that.
- All right, where is Mom gonna go?

656
00:32:54,724 --> 00:32:56,434
Where has she always wanted to go?

657
00:32:56,518 --> 00:32:57,894
My first thought was France...

658
00:32:57,977 --> 00:32:59,479
because, you know,
Dad never wanted to go there.

659
00:32:59,562 --> 00:33:02,315
But then I thought, maybe California.

660
00:33:02,399 --> 00:33:03,400
Why?

661
00:33:03,483 --> 00:33:06,069
Well, you know those friends of hers--
the husband's a periodontist?

662
00:33:06,152 --> 00:33:08,571
- The Schechners?
- Oh, the Schechners. That's it.

663
00:33:08,655 --> 00:33:09,989
I could not think of their names.

664
00:33:10,073 --> 00:33:11,533
She's gonna leave her husband
of 47 years...

665
00:33:11,616 --> 00:33:12,992
to be with
Marty and Charlotte Schechner?

666
00:33:13,076 --> 00:33:15,036
Well, it's possible, no?

667
00:33:15,078 --> 00:33:16,830
Yeah, but she's always
talking about them.

668
00:33:16,913 --> 00:33:19,124
Hold on a second. Hold on.
I got a call here.

669
00:33:20,333 --> 00:33:23,962
So...how's the motel?

670
00:33:24,045 --> 00:33:25,922
It's dark and smells like toast.

671
00:33:26,006 --> 00:33:27,340
It's Hillary.
Should I try to put her on?

672
00:33:27,424 --> 00:33:30,844
- How are you gonna put her on?
- Let me--Let me see. Did I lose you?

673
00:33:30,927 --> 00:33:32,470
- I'm here.
- Are you guys still there?

674
00:33:32,554 --> 00:33:34,556
- Still here.
- That's very impressive.

675
00:33:34,597 --> 00:33:36,182
- Look at that.
- So, what do you got?

676
00:33:36,266 --> 00:33:38,768
OK, listen to this.
I'm in Mom and Dad's house...

677
00:33:38,852 --> 00:33:39,978
I'm in the kitchen.

678
00:33:40,061 --> 00:33:45,108
I open up Mom's desk drawer--
big color travel brochure for Africa.

679
00:33:45,191 --> 00:33:47,277
- Africa?
- Stop it.

680
00:33:47,360 --> 00:33:50,405
I saw the brochure.
''Come, visit majestic Africa.''

681
00:33:50,447 --> 00:33:52,615
And she's got, like,
safari prices circled.

682
00:33:52,699 --> 00:33:54,451
Mom is not going to Africa.

683
00:33:54,534 --> 00:33:56,578
You see,
I think I have to agree with that one.

684
00:33:56,619 --> 00:33:58,496
Well, I talked to Bonnie,
and she doesn't believe...

685
00:33:58,580 --> 00:34:00,457
Mom would actually leave the country.

686
00:34:00,540 --> 00:34:02,792
Thinks she probably went
to a spa or something.

687
00:34:02,876 --> 00:34:03,918
Like, maybe Florida.

688
00:34:03,960 --> 00:34:05,628
OK, good. So, Paris, Kenya...

689
00:34:05,712 --> 00:34:07,839
and Boca Raton
we got it narrowed down to.

690
00:34:07,922 --> 00:34:11,259
Nobody's going to Boca Raton
this time of the year.

691
00:34:11,301 --> 00:34:13,011
It's 1 30 degrees there.

692
00:34:14,929 --> 00:34:16,139
What?

693
00:34:18,141 --> 00:34:20,435
OK, somebody just shoot me,
would you?

694
00:34:45,960 --> 00:34:49,047
Oh ho ho! That tree jumped out
and bit you pretty good! Ha ha ha!

695
00:34:49,130 --> 00:34:52,550
Listen, is there a--is there a car rental
place anywhere nearby?

696
00:34:52,634 --> 00:34:53,885
- Uh...
- Huh?

697
00:34:53,968 --> 00:34:55,136
- Rental car.
- Rental car?

698
00:34:55,220 --> 00:34:56,388
- Hmm.
- Car rental?

699
00:34:56,471 --> 00:34:59,516
- Hmm.
- A place where I can rent a car.

700
00:34:59,599 --> 00:35:01,726
I know what it is.
I was just thinking.

701
00:35:01,810 --> 00:35:02,811
I'm sorry.

702
00:35:02,852 --> 00:35:04,688
Hmm. Mm-mm-mm.

703
00:35:04,729 --> 00:35:08,483
Down in Emerson,
there's a car rental place.

704
00:35:08,525 --> 00:35:09,693
Benny!

705
00:35:09,776 --> 00:35:12,070
Uh, I think they're closed.

706
00:35:12,153 --> 00:35:15,824
You can drive in the other direction,
you go down to Pachaqua.

707
00:35:15,907 --> 00:35:18,410
I don't think they have
a car rental there.

708
00:35:18,493 --> 00:35:21,329
- Let me think. I'm just thinking.
- Benny, come here!

709
00:35:21,371 --> 00:35:22,622
I want to show you something!

710
00:35:22,706 --> 00:35:24,958
- I--I--
- Jesus.

711
00:35:25,041 --> 00:35:26,501
It'll come to me.

712
00:35:26,584 --> 00:35:29,170
This is not a thriving metropolis,
I'll tell you that.

713
00:35:29,212 --> 00:35:31,339
- There's a chicken place.
- you know what this is?

714
00:35:32,382 --> 00:35:36,553
This is a 1936 Ford.
Deluxe, it was called.

715
00:35:36,636 --> 00:35:38,638
Did you ever hear of Pachaqua?

716
00:35:38,722 --> 00:35:42,183
No. You know when the last time
I saw one of these?

717
00:35:42,267 --> 00:35:43,643
I was in college.

718
00:35:43,727 --> 00:35:46,312
I'm talkin' fifty-something years ago.

719
00:35:46,396 --> 00:35:49,065
I actually put down money
on a used one once--

720
00:35:49,149 --> 00:35:52,110
$300, which was a fortune back then.

721
00:35:52,193 --> 00:35:55,196
But my father,
he made me give it back.

722
00:35:56,364 --> 00:35:57,866
How come?

723
00:35:57,907 --> 00:36:00,326
You know, too flashy,
too much distraction.

724
00:36:00,410 --> 00:36:01,911
Who knows?

725
00:36:01,995 --> 00:36:05,790
What, you think you're the first one
who didn't understand his father?

726
00:36:07,167 --> 00:36:09,210
But, boy, is this beautiful.

727
00:36:09,294 --> 00:36:11,629
Look at that grill.

728
00:36:11,713 --> 00:36:14,466
Is that gorgeous or what?

729
00:36:14,549 --> 00:36:17,052
- You've got a good eye, sir!
- That's not a '36.

730
00:36:17,135 --> 00:36:18,428
This is a '40! Am I right?!

731
00:36:18,470 --> 00:36:20,722
That's right! A connoisseur, huh?

732
00:36:20,764 --> 00:36:24,142
I restored it myself! Rides like a dream!

733
00:36:24,225 --> 00:36:25,435
You don't say?

734
00:36:25,518 --> 00:36:28,772
If you're interested, make me an offer.

735
00:36:34,402 --> 00:36:36,863
I'm gonna do just that!

736
00:36:36,946 --> 00:36:39,157
You're gonna do what?

737
00:36:39,240 --> 00:36:42,077
I'm gonna buy me a Ford Deluxe.

738
00:36:42,118 --> 00:36:43,787
You're gonna--You're gonna buy it?

739
00:36:43,870 --> 00:36:48,208
Why not? Your car's all banged to shit.
We're in the middle of nowhere.

740
00:36:48,291 --> 00:36:50,585
Excuse me! Do you take Visa?

741
00:36:50,627 --> 00:36:52,587
Why--No, you can't just buy it!

742
00:36:52,629 --> 00:36:54,798
You don't know anything about this car.

743
00:36:54,881 --> 00:36:56,716
You don't--You don't know
how fast it goes.

744
00:36:56,800 --> 00:37:00,178
What's the hurry? I got no place to be.
You got some place to be?

745
00:37:00,261 --> 00:37:03,264
Don't you think we should get home
and see what's going on?

746
00:37:03,306 --> 00:37:07,018
See what? Your sisters are there.
They can make phone calls without you.

747
00:37:09,145 --> 00:37:10,397
I have work.

748
00:37:10,480 --> 00:37:13,650
Hey, you're the one
that wants to go write in the country.

749
00:37:13,733 --> 00:37:15,443
How much more country do you need?

750
00:37:16,611 --> 00:37:19,406
Your mother,
she ran off to God knows where.

751
00:37:19,489 --> 00:37:21,282
Your father's inconsolable.

752
00:37:21,324 --> 00:37:23,827
So console me. Am I asking a lot?

753
00:37:23,868 --> 00:37:26,454
- No, it's not that. It's just--
- So call home.

754
00:37:26,496 --> 00:37:30,166
You'll tell 'em you'll be back
as soon as your old man finds himself.

755
00:37:30,250 --> 00:37:32,293
If you want, we could find you, too.

756
00:37:32,335 --> 00:37:34,796
We could look for
the whole goddamn family.

757
00:37:34,838 --> 00:37:38,883
It makes no difference to me.
I got a car.

758
00:37:38,967 --> 00:37:41,177
So, what do you--what do you suggest?

759
00:37:41,261 --> 00:37:44,305
We make a trip. You and me.

760
00:37:46,641 --> 00:37:49,811
You want to check with your wife?

761
00:37:49,853 --> 00:37:52,689
I don't have to check with my wife.

762
00:37:52,772 --> 00:37:54,065
So?

763
00:37:54,149 --> 00:37:56,234
So?

764
00:38:00,280 --> 00:38:01,990
OK, buy the car.

765
00:38:13,877 --> 00:38:16,629
Oh, yeah. This car rides like a dream.

766
00:38:16,713 --> 00:38:18,256
Mmm.

767
00:38:18,340 --> 00:38:20,133
You smell that leather?

768
00:38:20,216 --> 00:38:21,343
I do.

769
00:38:21,426 --> 00:38:23,636
You see, it still has the old smell.

770
00:38:23,720 --> 00:38:24,971
Why that is, I don't know.

771
00:38:25,055 --> 00:38:29,684
You would think, fifty years,
it would lose the smell, but there it is--

772
00:38:29,768 --> 00:38:33,813
that good Ford smell.

773
00:38:33,897 --> 00:38:36,649
You know,
he was a big anti-Semite, Ford.

774
00:38:36,733 --> 00:38:38,109
You've mentioned this, yes.

775
00:38:38,193 --> 00:38:40,653
Yeah, but he made some beautiful cars.

776
00:38:40,737 --> 00:38:42,072
Yes, he did.

777
00:38:45,492 --> 00:38:47,035
You know,
your mother hates the way I drive.

778
00:38:47,118 --> 00:38:48,370
I know, I know.

779
00:38:48,411 --> 00:38:51,414
''You're driving too fast,''
''There's a curb there.''

780
00:38:51,498 --> 00:38:53,541
- I understand. Hey, listen.
- ''That was a stop sign.''

781
00:38:53,625 --> 00:38:55,210
OK, hey, believe me,
I've driven with you two.

782
00:38:55,293 --> 00:38:56,252
It's not a picnic, by the way.

783
00:38:56,336 --> 00:38:58,588
Now let me ask you. You're sitting there.

784
00:38:58,630 --> 00:39:01,591
- What?
- Am I such a terrible driver?

785
00:39:01,675 --> 00:39:03,301
No, you're not. Look at the road.

786
00:39:03,385 --> 00:39:04,636
Thank you.

787
00:39:05,929 --> 00:39:08,348
Oh, I love this car.

788
00:39:08,431 --> 00:39:12,644
The first one of these I saw,
this kid at school had one.

789
00:39:12,727 --> 00:39:18,358
Went out with this gorgeous girl,
Marion Savara.

790
00:39:18,441 --> 00:39:20,902
Her name I remember.

791
00:39:20,944 --> 00:39:23,947
- My God, what a knockout.
- Yeah?

792
00:39:24,030 --> 00:39:27,951
He would pull up in this big shiny car,
open her door...

793
00:39:28,034 --> 00:39:30,787
and out would come these legs.

794
00:39:30,870 --> 00:39:33,456
- Marion Savara.
- Marion Savara.

795
00:39:34,624 --> 00:39:36,751
I danced with her once.

796
00:39:36,835 --> 00:39:38,503
That was about it.

797
00:39:38,586 --> 00:39:40,588
You know why?
You didn't have this car then.

798
00:39:40,630 --> 00:39:44,092
You're exactly right.
You see, everybody's got something.

799
00:39:44,175 --> 00:39:46,511
Your mother never got
to the World's Fair.

800
00:39:46,594 --> 00:39:49,597
I never got a shot at Marion Savara.

801
00:39:49,639 --> 00:39:50,974
What are you going to do?

802
00:39:51,057 --> 00:39:52,517
What are you going to do?

803
00:39:59,024 --> 00:40:00,692
Look at us.

804
00:40:00,775 --> 00:40:04,446
Wherever we want,
whenever we want, huh?

805
00:40:04,487 --> 00:40:05,488
Ha ha ha.

806
00:40:09,784 --> 00:40:11,494
Did you ever do this with your dad?

807
00:40:11,536 --> 00:40:13,329
My dad? Never.

808
00:40:13,371 --> 00:40:15,331
- No?
- No, no, no, no.

809
00:40:15,415 --> 00:40:19,461
My dad worked.
That's all he knew--work.

810
00:40:19,502 --> 00:40:22,255
- And did you resent that?
- Oh, here we go.

811
00:40:22,339 --> 00:40:24,382
No, no, no. No, no, no.
I wasn't saying anything.

812
00:40:24,466 --> 00:40:25,759
Resent him?
What do you mean, resent?

813
00:40:25,842 --> 00:40:28,303
No, I didn't resent him.
That's the way it was.

814
00:40:28,345 --> 00:40:30,388
- He was my father.
- Yeah, I know.

815
00:40:30,472 --> 00:40:31,973
Why? Do you resent me?

816
00:40:32,057 --> 00:40:33,516
No, no. No, no, no, no, no.

817
00:40:33,600 --> 00:40:36,644
Because, you know,
we never did this before today, either.

818
00:40:36,686 --> 00:40:38,688
No, I know. Of course. I just...

819
00:40:38,772 --> 00:40:42,650
It's just something I think about
all the time now with my kids.

820
00:40:42,692 --> 00:40:44,527
They're growing up,
and I'm always thinking...

821
00:40:44,569 --> 00:40:47,781
you know,
what are they going to remember?

822
00:40:47,864 --> 00:40:49,199
Are we going to take them places--

823
00:40:49,240 --> 00:40:52,285
Are we going to do things
that they wished we didn't do...

824
00:40:52,369 --> 00:40:54,579
or are there going to be things
we didn't do...

825
00:40:54,662 --> 00:40:58,083
that they're going to grow up and say,
''Hey, how come we never did that?''

826
00:40:58,166 --> 00:41:00,794
You know?

827
00:41:00,877 --> 00:41:03,838
Is this what you do in therapy?

828
00:41:03,880 --> 00:41:06,132
No, no, no, no. It's--None of it--

829
00:41:06,216 --> 00:41:07,717
What is it that we didn't do?

830
00:41:07,801 --> 00:41:09,636
- Who?
- Me...with you and the girls.

831
00:41:09,719 --> 00:41:11,638
- No, you--
- What did we forget to do?

832
00:41:11,721 --> 00:41:14,557
- No, nothing. We didn't forget.
- No, I'm curious.

833
00:41:14,641 --> 00:41:17,352
I don't know. We...
We never went camping.

834
00:41:17,394 --> 00:41:19,229
Camping?
Who the hell goes camping?

835
00:41:19,312 --> 00:41:21,564
Sleep outside and crap in a bush?

836
00:41:21,648 --> 00:41:23,817
All right, well, then
we'll forget about that.

837
00:41:23,900 --> 00:41:25,527
Oh, sorry. I thought--No.

838
00:41:25,610 --> 00:41:27,737
No, no, no, no, no, no, no. I just--

839
00:41:27,821 --> 00:41:29,572
- I wasn't making a joke.
- It's not important.

840
00:41:29,656 --> 00:41:31,449
You always picture
fathers and sons, right?

841
00:41:31,533 --> 00:41:33,535
That's the thing you're supposed to do.

842
00:41:33,576 --> 00:41:37,622
You go camping together
and fishing at the fishing hole.

843
00:41:37,706 --> 00:41:40,375
OK. Come on.

844
00:41:40,417 --> 00:41:41,751
What are--What are you doing?

845
00:41:41,835 --> 00:41:43,253
What are you doing?

846
00:41:43,294 --> 00:41:46,297
I don't want you to resent
we never fished.

847
00:41:54,764 --> 00:41:57,684
- Here.
- No, that's part of the feather.

848
00:41:57,767 --> 00:41:59,310
- What?
- That's decoration.

849
00:41:59,394 --> 00:42:01,604
Mmm, I think you're wrong.

850
00:42:01,688 --> 00:42:02,981
- Oh.
- See? It dangles down.

851
00:42:03,064 --> 00:42:06,276
Oh, my God. You know,
there's a lot of pockets here.

852
00:42:06,359 --> 00:42:08,319
- Here.
- OK, now look.

853
00:42:08,403 --> 00:42:09,446
You see? It goes right there.

854
00:42:09,529 --> 00:42:10,572
- There?
- Yeah.

855
00:42:10,613 --> 00:42:12,615
- Right--Right there?
- Yes.

856
00:42:12,657 --> 00:42:15,118
- That's not the hole.
- What do you mean, it's not the hole?

857
00:42:15,160 --> 00:42:16,202
- There's got to be a thing where you...
- Yes, it is.

858
00:42:16,286 --> 00:42:17,412
- Of course.
- Wait a minute.

859
00:42:17,495 --> 00:42:18,705
Where does the worm go?

860
00:42:18,788 --> 00:42:20,874
There's no worms.
This is instead of worms.

861
00:42:20,957 --> 00:42:22,125
They forgot the worms?

862
00:42:22,208 --> 00:42:23,960
They didn't forget.
This is better than worms.

863
00:42:24,044 --> 00:42:26,254
Worms is the old--
This is what they do now.

864
00:42:26,296 --> 00:42:27,505
Oh, no worms.

865
00:42:27,589 --> 00:42:30,133
Yeah. Remember the guy told us?
You almost never use worms.

866
00:42:30,216 --> 00:42:32,761
- How about this here? That's big.
- Oh?

867
00:42:32,802 --> 00:42:34,888
The bigger the thing,
the bigger the fish, no?

868
00:42:34,971 --> 00:42:37,223
Hmm?
What if a little fish swallows it?

869
00:42:37,307 --> 00:42:39,893
- It could choke. See? I--
- Wait. Does a fish smell?

870
00:42:39,976 --> 00:42:43,605
They don't smell it, they see it.
How could they smell under the water?

871
00:42:43,688 --> 00:42:45,482
I don't know.

872
00:42:45,523 --> 00:42:47,817
The--Under the water don't smell?

873
00:42:47,901 --> 00:42:49,986
What? Here, hold this.

874
00:42:50,070 --> 00:42:51,696
Uh-huh.

875
00:42:51,780 --> 00:42:53,448
All right.

876
00:42:53,531 --> 00:42:55,116
- See, I just got--
- Oh, boy.

877
00:42:55,200 --> 00:42:56,618
No, no, no. I just got to put--Ow.

878
00:42:56,659 --> 00:42:59,287
- Oh, boy.
- All right, hold on.

879
00:42:59,371 --> 00:43:00,538
- Oh, boy.
- OK.

880
00:43:39,494 --> 00:43:41,329
Anything?

881
00:43:41,371 --> 00:43:43,373
- Nothing.
- All right.

882
00:43:43,456 --> 00:43:46,001
So, this is what it is.

883
00:43:47,377 --> 00:43:49,045
- I guess.
- Yeah.

884
00:43:53,758 --> 00:43:55,969
- Oh, my God.
- What?

885
00:43:56,052 --> 00:43:58,930
I think you just shot the first three bars
of "Moonlight in Vermont" there.

886
00:43:59,014 --> 00:44:00,390
There's nobody here.

887
00:44:00,473 --> 00:44:02,308
Who am I bothering?

888
00:44:08,148 --> 00:44:09,566
How are your toes?

889
00:44:09,607 --> 00:44:11,609
Not bad.

890
00:44:15,071 --> 00:44:17,449
Oh, I think I actually
got something here.

891
00:44:17,532 --> 00:44:18,616
Hold him up. Hold still.

892
00:44:18,700 --> 00:44:19,909
- Huh?
- Hold still.

893
00:44:19,993 --> 00:44:21,870
What--What are you doing?

894
00:44:21,911 --> 00:44:24,164
- He's still alive.
- Of course he's still alive.

895
00:44:24,247 --> 00:44:25,248
I just pulled him out of--
What are you hitting him for?

896
00:44:25,331 --> 00:44:26,416
I'm not hitting him.

897
00:44:26,499 --> 00:44:28,084
Yeah, you just smacked--
Why would you hit a fish?

898
00:44:28,168 --> 00:44:29,586
Poor thing can't breathe.

899
00:44:29,669 --> 00:44:30,754
Oh, what, and you think hitting him's
going to help him?

900
00:44:30,837 --> 00:44:33,340
- Give me the thing. Give me the thing.
- Don't--Don't hit him.

901
00:44:33,423 --> 00:44:35,884
- Don't--Don't hurt it.
- I'll let him catch his breath a little.

902
00:44:35,925 --> 00:44:37,093
- What?
- Not his breath...

903
00:44:37,177 --> 00:44:39,179
but you know what I mean.

904
00:44:39,262 --> 00:44:41,723
Yeah, little fishy. You want to go, huh?

905
00:44:41,765 --> 00:44:43,767
You want to go? Go ahead.

906
00:44:43,850 --> 00:44:45,393
We were just kidding.

907
00:44:52,734 --> 00:44:55,070
- You had enough fishing?
- I could be done.

908
00:45:39,781 --> 00:45:42,367
Huh? Yeah, he's--he's all right, actually.

909
00:45:42,450 --> 00:45:43,702
I'm better than all right.

910
00:45:43,785 --> 00:45:45,954
This is the best I've been
since I don't know when.

911
00:45:45,995 --> 00:45:47,872
Your mother
should leave me more often.

912
00:45:47,956 --> 00:45:49,082
Mom should leave him
more often, he said.

913
00:45:49,165 --> 00:45:51,793
Why do you keep saying
what I'm saying? Let me talk.

914
00:45:51,876 --> 00:45:54,754
All right, he wants to talk to you.
I don't know.

915
00:45:54,838 --> 00:45:56,214
Hello, sweetheart.

916
00:45:56,297 --> 00:46:00,301
Listen, if your husband doesn't
check in every 45 minutes...

917
00:46:00,343 --> 00:46:03,805
you won't be beside yourself
with worry.

918
00:46:03,847 --> 00:46:06,266
I agree with you 100%.

919
00:46:06,349 --> 00:46:09,519
Ha ha ha. All right. Bye-bye.

920
00:46:09,602 --> 00:46:10,895
And what?

921
00:46:10,979 --> 00:46:12,856
She's a very sweet girl, your wife.

922
00:46:12,939 --> 00:46:14,983
Agree what?
What'd she just say to you?

923
00:46:15,025 --> 00:46:17,360
She said you can be
quite a pain in the ass...

924
00:46:17,402 --> 00:46:19,904
and I shouldn't take it personal.

925
00:46:19,988 --> 00:46:21,322
So sweet.

926
00:46:36,546 --> 00:46:38,548
Wait a minute, wait a minute.
Listen to you.

927
00:46:38,590 --> 00:46:41,092
Now, the point is,
if a person is determined...

928
00:46:41,176 --> 00:46:43,345
to be unhappy
and angry their whole life...

929
00:46:43,428 --> 00:46:45,722
then you know what?
That's their problem.

930
00:46:45,805 --> 00:46:48,183
- Jeez, Pop.
- What?

931
00:46:48,224 --> 00:46:51,394
So, if Mom was unhappy,
you didn't care?

932
00:46:51,478 --> 00:46:53,396
I never said I didn't care.

933
00:46:53,480 --> 00:46:55,523
You just said, if she's unhappy,
that's her problem.

934
00:46:55,607 --> 00:46:58,693
- That's her problem, that's right.
- OK.

935
00:46:58,735 --> 00:47:01,488
- What? So I'm the schmuck?
- No, but--

936
00:47:01,571 --> 00:47:04,366
No, it's my fault.
She's unhappy because of me, right?

937
00:47:04,407 --> 00:47:06,284
- No, I didn't say that.
- Well, that's what you think.

938
00:47:06,368 --> 00:47:08,036
- No. No, I'm not saying that.
- Yes, it is.

939
00:47:08,078 --> 00:47:09,746
- Come on, that's what you think.
- No, but I--

940
00:47:09,829 --> 00:47:12,874
Well, I'm going to tell you something now
that I never said before.

941
00:47:12,916 --> 00:47:16,544
I think she was unhappy already
when I met her.

942
00:47:16,586 --> 00:47:18,213
That's right.

943
00:47:18,254 --> 00:47:20,882
And all the time before that,
growing up.

944
00:47:20,924 --> 00:47:23,593
I think she was an unhappy girl.

945
00:47:23,677 --> 00:47:26,054
Remember her father?

946
00:47:26,096 --> 00:47:28,431
- No. He--He was--He died.
- Oh, yeah, of course.

947
00:47:28,515 --> 00:47:32,560
Yeah. Well, he was
a real sourpuss of a guy.

948
00:47:32,602 --> 00:47:34,813
Nice enough, but a sourpuss.

949
00:47:34,896 --> 00:47:36,856
And your grandmother, well...

950
00:47:36,940 --> 00:47:39,818
she wasn't the cheeriest person
in the world, either.

951
00:47:39,901 --> 00:47:42,237
I'm not saying
they didn't have problems...

952
00:47:42,278 --> 00:47:47,075
but it was not a happy house.

953
00:47:47,117 --> 00:47:50,120
And your mother, by the time
she set out into the world...

954
00:47:50,203 --> 00:47:53,915
she already had this, I don't know...

955
00:47:53,998 --> 00:47:58,962
I just never got the impression
she was ever happy.

956
00:48:04,342 --> 00:48:06,511
Well, maybe that explains...

957
00:48:06,594 --> 00:48:08,847
why she wanted so much
to be happy with you.

958
00:48:08,930 --> 00:48:11,599
- OK. OK.
- Huh?

959
00:48:11,641 --> 00:48:13,143
But, listen.

960
00:48:13,184 --> 00:48:14,978
I was in the same marriage...

961
00:48:15,020 --> 00:48:17,439
and I was happy.

962
00:48:17,480 --> 00:48:19,566
Yes, you were happy,
but that's the point.

963
00:48:19,649 --> 00:48:20,942
Well, the point is, see...

964
00:48:20,984 --> 00:48:22,694
if you had made just, like,
a little more of an effort--

965
00:48:22,777 --> 00:48:24,946
Oh, peaches.

966
00:48:28,783 --> 00:48:31,494
Oh, my God. That's a peach.

967
00:48:31,578 --> 00:48:33,371
You're really not going to try one?

968
00:48:33,455 --> 00:48:35,165
Can't. Allergic.

969
